 events that took place late in the seventeenth century, when Native groups and Europeans began to have their first sustained contact in the region. Wade identifies twenty-one Native groups, including the Jumano, who inhabited the Edwards Plateau at that time. She offers evidence that the groups had sophisticated social and cultural mechanisms, including extensive information networks, ladino cultural brokers, broad-based coalitions, and individuals with dual-ethnic status. She also tracks the eastern movement of Spanish colonizers into the Edwards Plateau region, explores the relationships among Native groups and between those groups and European colonizers, and develops a timeline that places isolated events and singular individuals within broad historical processes.  afunded by Wade  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aIndians of North AmericazTexaszEdwards PlateauxHistory. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Archaeology.2bisacsh1 aHester, Thomas R.1 aHester, Thomas R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWade, Maria F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb2 aWadeefunder.4fnd4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/fnd40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780292796317423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780292796317/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK